         <abstract>
            <p>This paper considers in general the problem of finding the minimum of a given functional f(u) over a set B by approximately minimizing a sequence of functionals f&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;(u&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;) over a "discretized" set B&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;; theorems are given proving the convergence of the approximating points u&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; in B&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt; to the desired point u in B. Applications are given to the Rayleigh-Ritz method, regularization, Chebyshev solution of differential equations, and the calculus of variations.</p>
          </abstract>
